# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: koa
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:koa/express-js] The original author, TJ Holowaychuk, described it as a Sinatra-inspired server, meaning that it is relatively minimal with many features available as plugins.
[src:koa/express-js] Express is the back-end component of popular development stacks like the MEAN, MERN or MEVN stack, together with the MongoDB database software and a JavaScript front-end framework or library.
[src:koa/express-js] Express.js was founded by TJ Holowaychuk.
[src:koa/express-js] The initial versions were created in early 2010, and milestone version 1 was released later that year.
[src:koa/express-js] In June 2014, rights to manage the project were acquired by StrongLoop.
[src:koa/express-js] StrongLoop was acquired by IBM in September 2015; in January 2016, IBM announced that it would place Express.js under the stewardship of the Node.js Foundation incubator.
[src:koa/express-js] In July 2014, work began towards milestone version 5.
[src:koa/express-js] After ten years of development it was released in October 2024.
[src:koa/express-js] Express.js is used by Fox Sports, PayPal, Uber and IBM.
[src:koa/express-js] The following program will respond to HTTP GET requests with the text "Hi, your request has been received", and listen to the port the program is running on (in this case, port 2000).
[src:koa/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:koa/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:koa/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:koa/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:koa/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:koa/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:koa/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:koa/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:koa/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:koa/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:koa/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:koa/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:koa/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:koa/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:koa/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:koa/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:koa/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:koa/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:koa/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:koa/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:koa/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:koa/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:koa/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:koa/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:koa/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:koa/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:koa/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:koa/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:koa/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:koa/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:koa/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:koa/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:koa/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:koa/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:koa/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:koa/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:koa/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:koa/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:koa/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:koa/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:koa/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:koa/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:koa/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:koa/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:koa/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:koa/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:koa/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:koa/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:koa/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:koa/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:koa/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:koa/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:koa/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:koa/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:koa/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:koa/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:koa/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:koa/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:koa/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:koa/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:koa/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:koa/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:koa/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:koa/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:koa/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:koa/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:koa/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:koa/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:koa/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:koa/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:koa/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:koa/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:koa/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:koa/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:koa/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:koa/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:koa/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:koa/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:koa/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:koa/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:koa/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:koa/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:koa/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:koa/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:koa/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:koa/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:koa/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:koa/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:koa/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:koa/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:koa/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:koa/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:koa/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:koa/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:koa/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:koa/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:koa/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:koa/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:koa/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:koa/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:koa/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:koa/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:koa/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:koa/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:koa/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:koa/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:koa/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:koa/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:koa/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:koa/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:koa/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:koa/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:koa/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:koa/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:koa/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:koa/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:koa/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:koa/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:koa/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:koa/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:koa/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:koa/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:koa/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:koa/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:koa/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:koa/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:koa/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:koa/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:koa/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:koa/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:koa/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:koa/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:koa/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:koa/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:koa/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:koa/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:koa/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:koa/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:koa/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:koa/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:koa/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:koa/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:koa/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:koa/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:koa/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:koa/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
[src:koa/javascript] The function can access them through formal parameters and also through the local `arguments` object.
[src:koa/javascript] Variadic functions can also be created by using the `bind` method.
[src:koa/javascript] Like in many scripting languages, arrays and objects (associative arrays in other languages) can each be created with a succinct shortcut syntax.
[src:koa/javascript] In fact, these literals form the basis of the JSON data format.
[src:koa/javascript] JavaScript supports regular expressions for text searches and manipulation.
[src:koa/javascript] A built-in Promise object provides functionality for handling promises and associating handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual result.
[src:koa/javascript] JavaScript supplies combinator methods, which allow developers to combine multiple JavaScript promises and do operations based on different scenarios.
[src:koa/javascript] The methods introduced are: Promise.race, Promise.all, Promise.allSettled and Promise.any.
[src:koa/javascript] Async/await allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:koa/javascript] Asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written, with minimal overhead, structured similarly to traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:koa/javascript] Variables in JavaScript can be defined using either the `var`, `let` or `const` keywords.
[src:koa/javascript] Variables defined without keywords will be defined at the global scope.
[src:koa/javascript] Arrow functions were first introduced in 6th Edition – ECMAScript 2015.
[src:koa/javascript] They shorten the syntax for writing functions in JavaScript.
[src:koa/javascript] Arrow functions are anonymous, so a variable is needed to refer to them in order to invoke them after their creation, unless surrounded by parenthesis and executed immediately.
[src:koa/javascript] Here is an example of JavaScript syntax.
[src:koa/javascript] Note the comments in the examples above, all of which were preceded with two forward slashes.
[src:koa/javascript] More examples can be found at the Wikibooks page on JavaScript syntax examples.
[src:koa/javascript] JavaScript and the DOM provide the potential for malicious authors to deliver scripts to run on a client computer via the Web.
[src:koa/javascript] Browser authors minimize this risk using two restrictions.
[src:koa/javascript] First, scripts run in a sandbox in which they can only perform Web-related actions, not general-purpose programming tasks like creating files.
[src:koa/javascript] Second, scripts are constrained by the same-origin policy: scripts from one website do not have access to information such as usernames, passwords, or cookies sent to another site.
[src:koa/javascript] Most JavaScript-related security bugs are breaches of either the same origin policy or the sandbox.
[src:koa/javascript] There are subsets of general JavaScript—ADsafe, Secure ECMAScript (SES)—that provide greater levels of security, especially on code created by third parties (such as advertisements).
[src:koa/javascript] Closure Toolkit is another project for safe embedding and isolation of third-party JavaScript and HTML.
[src:koa/javascript] Content Security Policy is the main intended method of ensuring that only trusted code is executed on a Web page.
[src:koa/javascript] A common JavaScript-related security problem is cross-site scripting (XSS), a violation of the same-origin policy.
[src:koa/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker can cause a target Website, such as an online banking website, to include a malicious script in the webpage presented to a victim.
[src:koa/javascript] The script in this example can then access the banking application with the privileges of the victim, potentially disclosing secret information or transferring money without the victim's authorization.
[src:koa/javascript] One important solution to XSS vulnerabilities is HTML sanitization.
[src:koa/javascript] Some browsers include partial protection against *reflected* XSS attacks, in which the attacker provides a URL including malicious script.
[src:koa/javascript] However, even users of those browsers are vulnerable to other XSS attacks, such as those where the malicious code is stored in a database.
[src:koa/javascript] Only correct design of Web applications on the server-side can fully prevent XSS.
[src:koa/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities can also occur because of implementation mistakes by browser authors.
[src:koa/javascript] Another cross-site vulnerability is cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:koa/javascript] In CSRF, code on an attacker's site tricks the victim's browser into taking actions the user did not intend at a target site (like transferring money at a bank).
[src:koa/javascript] When target sites rely solely on cookies for request authentication, requests originating from code on the attacker's site can carry the same valid login credentials of the initiating user.
[src:koa/javascript] In general, the solution to CSRF is to require an authentication value in a hidden form field, and not only in the cookies, to authenticate any request that might have lasting effects.
[src:koa/javascript] Checking the HTTP Referrer header can also help.
[src:koa/javascript] "JavaScript hijacking" is a type of CSRF attack in which a `<script>` tag on an attacker's site exploits a page on the victim's site that returns private information such as JSON or JavaScript.
[src:koa/javascript] Developers of client-server applications must recognize that untrusted clients may be under the control of attackers.
[src:koa/javascript] The author of an application should not assume that their JavaScript code will run as intended (or at all) because any secret embedded in the code could be extracted by a determined adversary.
[src:koa/javascript] Package management systems such as npm and Bower are popular with JavaScript developers.
[src:koa/javascript] Such systems allow a developer to easily manage their program's dependencies upon other developers' program libraries.
[src:koa/javascript] Developers trust that the maintainers of the libraries will keep them secure and up to date, but that is not always the case.
[src:koa/javascript] A vulnerability has emerged because of this blind trust.
[src:koa/javascript] Relied-upon libraries can have new releases that cause bugs or vulnerabilities to appear in all programs that rely upon the libraries.
[src:koa/javascript] Inversely, a library can go unpatched with known vulnerabilities out in the wild.
[src:koa/javascript] In a study done looking over a sample of 133,000 websites, researchers found 37% of the websites included a library with at least one known vulnerability.
[src:koa/javascript] This occurred in March 2016 when Azer Koçulu removed his repository from npm.
[src:koa/javascript] This caused tens of thousands of programs and websites depending upon his libraries to break.
[src:koa/javascript] JavaScript provides an interface to a wide range of browser capabilities, some of which may have flaws such as buffer overflows.
[src:koa/javascript] These flaws can allow attackers to write scripts that would run any code they wish on the user's system.
[src:koa/javascript] This code is not by any means limited to another JavaScript application.
[src:koa/javascript] For example, a buffer overrun exploit can allow an attacker to gain access to the operating system's API with superuser privileges.
[src:koa/javascript] These flaws have affected major browsers including Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Safari.
[src:koa/javascript] Plugins, such as video players, Adobe Flash, and the wide range of ActiveX controls enabled by default in Microsoft Internet Explorer, may also have flaws exploitable via JavaScript (such flaws have been exploited in the past).
[src:koa/javascript] In Windows Vista, Microsoft has attempted to contain the risks of bugs such as buffer overflows by running the Internet Explorer process with limited privileges.
[src:koa/javascript] Google Chrome similarly confines its page renderers to their own "sandbox".
[src:koa/javascript] Web browsers are capable of running JavaScript outside the sandbox, with the privileges necessary to, for example, create or delete files.
[src:koa/javascript] Such privileges are not intended to be granted to code from the Web.
[src:koa/javascript] Incorrectly granting privileges to JavaScript from the Web has played a role in vulnerabilities in both Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:koa/javascript] In Windows XP Service Pack 2, Microsoft demoted JScript's privileges in Internet Explorer.
[src:koa/javascript] Microsoft Windows allows JavaScript source files on a computer's hard drive to be launched as general-purpose, non-sandboxed programs (see: Windows Script Host).
[src:koa/javascript] This makes JavaScript (like VBScript) a theoretically viable vector for a Trojan horse, although JavaScript Trojan horses are uncommon in practice.
[src:koa/javascript] In 2015, a JavaScript-based proof-of-concept implementation of a rowhammer attack was described in a paper by security researchers.
[src:koa/javascript] In 2017, a JavaScript-based attack via browser was demonstrated that could bypass ASLR.
[src:koa/javascript] In 2018, the paper that announced the Spectre attacks against Speculative Execution in Intel and other processors included a JavaScript implementation.
[src:koa/javascript] Important tools have evolved with the language.
[src:koa/javascript] A common misconception is that JavaScript is directly related to Java.
[src:koa/javascript] Both indeed have a C-like syntax (the C language being their most immediate common ancestor language).
[src:koa/javascript] They are also typically sandboxed, and JavaScript was designed with Java's syntax and standard library in mind.
[src:koa/javascript] In particular, all Java keywords were reserved in original JavaScript, JavaScript's standard library follows Java's naming conventions, and JavaScript's `Math` and `Date` objects are based on classes from Java 1.0.
[src:koa/javascript] Both languages first appeared in 1995, but Java was developed by James Gosling of Sun Microsystems and JavaScript by Brendan Eich of Netscape Communications.
[src:koa/javascript] The differences between the two languages are more prominent than their similarities.
[src:koa/javascript] Java has static typing, while JavaScript's typing is dynamic.
[src:koa/javascript] Java is loaded from compiled bytecode, while JavaScript is loaded as human-readable source code.
[src:koa/javascript] Java's objects are class-based, while JavaScript's are prototype-based.
[src:koa/javascript] Finally, Java did not support functional programming until Java 8, while JavaScript has done so from the beginning, being influenced by Scheme.
[src:koa/javascript] JSON is a data format derived from JavaScript; hence the name JavaScript Object Notation.
[src:koa/javascript] It is a widely used format supported by many other programming languages.
[src:koa/javascript] Many websites are JavaScript-heavy, so transpilers have been created to convert code written in other languages, which can aid the development process.
[src:koa/javascript] TypeScript and CoffeeScript are two notable languages that transpile to JavaScript.
[src:koa/javascript] WebAssembly is a newer language with a bytecode format designed to complement JavaScript, especially the performance-critical portions of web page scripts.
[src:koa/javascript] All of the major JavaScript engines support WebAssembly, which runs in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
