[src:koa/koajs-com] A Koa `Request` object is an abstraction on top of Node's vanilla request object, providing additional functionality that is useful for every day HTTP server development.
[src:koa/koajs-com] This is the same as the `headers` field on Node's `http.IncomingMessage`.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Set request method, useful for implementing middleware such as `methodOverride()`.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Return request Content-Length as a number when present, or `undefined`.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Set request URL, useful for url rewrites.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Get origin of URL, include `protocol` and `host`.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Get full request URL, include `protocol`, `host` and `url`.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Set request pathname and retain query-string when present.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Supports `X-Forwarded-Host` when `app.proxy` is **true**, otherwise `Host` is used.
[src:koa/koajs-com] If host is IPv6, Koa delegates parsing to WHATWG URL API, *Note* This may impact performance.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Get request `Content-Type` void of parameters such as "charset".
[src:koa/koajs-com] Get parsed query-string, returning an empty object when no query-string is present.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Note that this getter does *not* support nested parsing.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Note that this setter does *not* support nested objects.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Check if a request cache is "fresh", aka the contents have not changed.
[src:koa/koajs-com] This method is for cache negotiation between `If-None-Match` / `ETag`, and `If-Modified-Since` and `Last-Modified`.
[src:koa/koajs-com] It should be referenced after setting one or more of these response headers.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Return request protocol, "https" or "http".
[src:koa/koajs-com] Supports `X-Forwarded-Proto` when `app.proxy` is **true**.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Shorthand for `ctx.protocol == "https"` to check if a request was issued via TLS.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Supports `X-Forwarded-For` when `app.proxy` is **true**.
[src:koa/koajs-com] When `X-Forwarded-For` is present and `app.proxy` is enabled an array of these ips is returned, ordered from upstream -> downstream.
[src:koa/koajs-com] When disabled an empty array is returned.
[src:koa/koajs-com] For example if the value were "client, proxy1, proxy2", you would receive the array `["client", "proxy1", "proxy2"]`.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Most of the reverse proxy(nginx) set x-forwarded-for via `proxy_add_x_forwarded_for`, which poses a certain security risk.
[src:koa/koajs-com] A malicious attacker can forge a client's ip address by forging a `X-Forwarded-For`request header.
[src:koa/koajs-com] The request sent by the client has an `X-Forwarded-For` request header for 'forged'.
[src:koa/koajs-com] After being forwarded by the reverse proxy, `request.ips` will be ['forged', 'client', 'proxy1', 'proxy2'].
[src:koa/koajs-com] Koa offers two options to avoid being bypassed.
[src:koa/koajs-com] If you can control the reverse proxy, you can avoid bypassing by adjusting the configuration, or use the `app.proxyIpHeader` provided by koa to avoid reading `x-forwarded-for` to get ips.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Subdomains are the dot-separated parts of the host before the main domain of the app.
[src:koa/koajs-com] By default, the domain of the app is assumed to be the last two parts of the host.
[src:koa/koajs-com] This can be changed by setting `app.subdomainOffset`.
[src:koa/koajs-com] For example, if the domain is "tobi.ferrets.example.com": If `app.subdomainOffset` is not set, `ctx.subdomains` is `["ferrets", "tobi"]`.
[src:koa/koajs-com] If `app.subdomainOffset` is 3, `ctx.subdomains` is `["tobi"]`.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Check if the incoming request contains the "Content-Type" header field, and it contains any of the give mime `type`s.
[src:koa/koajs-com] If there is no request body, `null` is returned.
[src:koa/koajs-com] If there is no content type, or the match fails `false` is returned.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Otherwise, it returns the matching content-type.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Koa's `request` object includes helpful content negotiation utilities powered by accepts and negotiator.
[src:koa/koajs-com] If no types are supplied, **all** acceptable types are returned.
[src:koa/koajs-com] If multiple types are supplied, the best match will be returned.
[src:koa/koajs-com] If no matches are found, a `false` is returned, and you should send a `406 "Not Acceptable"` response to the client.
[src:koa/koajs-com] In the case of missing accept headers where any type is acceptable, the first type will be returned.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Thus, the order of types you supply is important.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Check if the given `type(s)` is acceptable, returning the best match when true, otherwise `false`.
[src:koa/koajs-com] The `type` value may be one or more mime type string such as "application/json", the extension name such as "json", or an array `["json", "html", "text/plain"]`.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Check if `encodings` are acceptable, returning the best match when true, otherwise `false`.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Note that you should include `identity` as one of the encodings!
[src:koa/koajs-com] Note that the `identity` encoding (which means no encoding) could be unacceptable if the client explicitly sends `identity;q=0`.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Although this is an edge case, you should still handle the case where this method returns `false`.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Check if `charsets` are acceptable, returning the best match when true, otherwise `false`.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Check if `langs` are acceptable, returning the best match when true, otherwise `false`.
[src:koa/koajs-com] Check if the request is idempotent (e.g. a `GET`, `HEAD`, etc. request).
[src:koa/koajs-com] Return request header with case-insensitive `field`.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware often enables interoperability between applications that run on different operating systems, by supplying services so the application can exchange data in a standards-based way.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware sits "in the middle" between application software that may be working on different operating systems.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] It is similar to the middle layer of a three-tier single system architecture, except that it is stretched across multiple systems or applications.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Examples include EAI software, telecommunications software, transaction monitors, and messaging-and-queueing software.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] The distinction between operating system and middleware functionality is, to some extent, arbitrary.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] While core kernel functionality can only be provided by the operating system itself, some functionality previously provided by separately sold middleware is now integrated in operating systems.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] A typical example is the TCP/IP stack for telecommunications, nowadays included virtually in every operating system.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware is defined as software that provides a link between separate software applications.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] It is sometimes referred to as plumbing because it connects two applications and passes data between them.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware allows data contained in one database to be accessed through another.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] This makes it particularly useful for enterprise application integration and data integration tasks.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware gained popularity in the 1980s as a solution to the problem of how to link newer applications to older legacy systems, although the term had been in use since 1968.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] It also facilitated distributed processing, the connection of multiple applications to create a larger application, usually over a network.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] when compared to the operating system and network services.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware offers some unique technological advantages for business and industry.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] For example, traditional database systems are usually deployed in closed environments where users access the system only via a restricted network or intranet (e.g., an enterprise’s internal network).
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] With the phenomenal growth of the World Wide Web, users can access virtually any database for which they have proper access rights from anywhere in the world.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware addresses the problem of varying levels of interoperability among different database structures.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware facilitates transparent access to legacy database management systems (DBMSs) or applications via a web server without regard to database-specific characteristics.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Businesses frequently use middleware applications to link information from departmental databases, such as payroll, sales, and accounting, or databases housed in multiple geographic locations.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] In the highly competitive healthcare community, laboratories make extensive use of middleware applications for data mining, laboratory information system (LIS) backup, and to combine systems during hospital mergers.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware helps bridge the gap between separate LISs in a newly formed healthcare network following a hospital buyout.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware can help software developers avoid having to write application programming interfaces (API) for every control program, by serving as an independent programming interface for their applications.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] For Future Internet network operation through traffic monitoring in multi-domain scenarios, using mediator tools (middleware) is a powerful help since they allow operators, searchers and service providers to supervise Quality of service and analyse eventual failures in telecommunication services.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Finally, e-commerce uses middleware to assist in handling rapid and secure transactions over many different types of computer environments.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] In short, middleware has become a critical element across a broad range of industries, thanks to its ability to bring together resources across dissimilar networks or computing platforms.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] In 2004 members of the European Broadcasting Union (EBU) carried out a study of Middleware with respect to system integration in broadcast environments.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] This involved system design engineering experts from 10 major European broadcasters working over a 12-month period to understand the effect of predominantly software-based products to media production and broadcasting system design techniques.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] The resulting reports Tech 3300 and Tech 3300s were published and are freely available from the EBU web site.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Message-oriented middleware (MOM) is middleware where transactions or event notifications are delivered between disparate systems or components by way of messages, often via an enterprise messaging system.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] With MOM, messages sent to the client are collected and stored until they are acted upon, while the client continues with other processing.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] software may queue, duplicate, translate and deliver messages to disparate systems or components in a messaging system.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Intelligent Middleware (IMW) provides real-time intelligence and event management through intelligent agents.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] The IMW manages the real-time processing of high volume sensor signals and turns these signals into intelligent and actionable business information.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] The actionable information is then delivered in end-user power dashboards to individual users or is pushed to systems within or outside the enterprise.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] It is able to support various heterogeneous types of hardware and software and provides an API for interfacing with external systems.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] It should have a highly scalable, distributed architecture which embeds intelligence throughout the network to transform raw data systematically into actionable and relevant knowledge.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] It can also be packaged with tools to view and manage operations and build advanced network applications most effectively.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Content-centric middleware offers a simple *provider-consumer* abstraction through which applications can issue requests for uniquely identified content, without worrying about where or how it is obtained.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Juno is one example, which allows applications to generate content requests associated with high-level delivery requirements.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] The middleware then adapts the underlying delivery to access the content from sources that are best suited to matching the requirements.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] This is therefore similar to Publish/subscribe middleware, as well as the Content-centric networking paradigm.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] middleware enables a client to use services running on remote systems.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] middleware, it is possible for applications to send objects and request services in an object-oriented system.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] is middleware between applications and database servers.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] integration interface that operates between embedded applications, the embedded operating system, and external applications.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Policy appliance is a generic term referring to any form of middleware that manages policy rules.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] They can mediate between data owners or producers, data aggregators, and data users.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Among heterogeneous institutional systems or networks they may be used to enforce, reconcile, and monitor agreed information management policies and laws across systems (or between jurisdictions) with divergent information policies or needs.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Policy appliances support policy-based information management processes by enabling rules-based processing, selective disclosure, and accountability and oversight.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] IBM, Red Hat, Oracle Corporation and Microsoft are some of the vendors that provide middleware software.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Vendors such as Axway, SAP, TIBCO, Informatica, Objective Interface Systems, Pervasive, ScaleOut Software and webMethods were specifically founded to provide more niche middleware solutions.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Groups such as the Apache Software Foundation, OpenSAF, the ObjectWeb Consortium (now OW2) and OASIS' AMQP encourage the development of open source middleware.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Microsoft .NET "Framework" architecture is essentially "Middleware" with typical middleware functions distributed between the various products, with most inter-computer interaction by industry standards, open APIs or RAND software licence.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] Solace provides middleware in purpose-built hardware for implementations that may experience scale.
[src:koa/middleware-distributed-applications] StormMQ provides Message Oriented Middleware as a service.
[src:koa/node-js] Node.js allows developers to use JavaScript for writing command line tools and server-side scripting.
[src:koa/node-js] Running Javascript on the server is commonly used to generate dynamic web page content before the page is sent to the user's web browser.
[src:koa/node-js] Consequently, Node.js represents a "JavaScript everywhere" paradigm, unifying web-application development around a single programming language, as opposed to using different languages for the server- versus client-side programming.
[src:koa/node-js] Node.js has an event-driven architecture capable of asynchronous I/O.
[src:koa/node-js] These design choices aim to optimize throughput and scalability in web applications with many input/output operations, as well as for real-time Web applications (e.g., real-time communication programs and browser games).
[src:koa/node-js] The Node.js distributed development project was previously governed by the Node.js Foundation, and has now merged with the JS Foundation to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:koa/node-js] OpenJS Foundation is facilitated by the Linux Foundation's Collaborative Projects program.
[src:koa/node-js] Node.js was initially written by Ryan Dahl in 2009, about 13 years after the introduction of the first server-side JavaScript environment, Netscape's LiveWire Pro Web.
[src:koa/node-js] The initial release supported only Linux and Mac OS X.
[src:koa/node-js] Its development and maintenance was led by Dahl and later sponsored by Joyent.
[src:koa/node-js] Dahl demonstrated the project at the inaugural European JSConf on November 8, 2009.
[src:koa/node-js] Node.js combined Google's V8 JavaScript engine, an event loop, and a low-level I/O API.
[src:koa/node-js] In January 2010, a package manager was introduced for the Node.js environment called npm.
[src:koa/node-js] The package manager allows programmers to publish and share Node.js packages, along with the accompanying source code, and is designed to simplify the installation, update and uninstallation of packages.
[src:koa/node-js] In June 2011, Microsoft and Joyent implemented a native Windows version of Node.js.
[src:koa/node-js] The first Node.js build supporting Windows was released in July 2011.
[src:koa/node-js] In January 2012, Dahl yielded management of the project to npm creator Isaac Schlueter.
[src:koa/node-js] In January 2014, Schlueter announced that Timothy J.
[src:koa/node-js] In December 2014, Fedor Indutny created io.js, a fork of Node.js created because of dissatisfaction with Joyent's governance as an open-governance alternative with a separate technical committee.
[src:koa/node-js] The goal was to enable a structure that would be more receptive to community input, including the updating of io.js with the latest Google V8 JavaScript engine releases, diverging from Node.js's approach at that time.
[src:koa/node-js] The Node.js Foundation, formed to reconcile Node.js and io.js under a unified banner, was announced in February 2015.
[src:koa/node-js] The merger was realized in September 2015 with Node.js v0.12 and io.js v3.3 combining into Node v4.0.
[src:koa/node-js] This merge brought V8 ES6 features into Node.js and started a long-term support release cycle.
[src:koa/node-js] By 2016, the io.js website recommended returning to Node.js and announced no further io.js releases, effectively ending the fork and solidifying the merger's success.
[src:koa/node-js] In 2019, the JS Foundation and Node.js Foundation merged to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:koa/node-js] The Node.js logo features a green hexagon with overlapping bands to represent the cross-platform nature of the runtime.
[src:koa/node-js] The Rocket Turtle was chosen as the official Node.js mascot in February 2024 following a design contest.
[src:koa/node-js] Node.js allows the creation of web servers and networking tools using JavaScript and a collection of "modules" that handle various core functionalities.
[src:koa/node-js] Modules are provided for file system I/O, networking (DNS, HTTP, TCP, TLS/SSL or UDP), binary data (buffers), cryptography functions, data streams and other core functions.
[src:koa/node-js] Node.js's modules use an API designed to reduce the complexity of writing server applications.
[src:koa/node-js] Since version 22.6.0, Node.js natively supports both JavaScript and TypeScript, allowing TypeScript files to be executed without a separate compilation step.
[src:koa/node-js] The TypeScript support was contributed by Node.js TSC member Marco Ippolito.
[src:koa/node-js] In addition, many compile-to-JS languages are available, allowing Node.js applications to also be written in CoffeeScript, Dart, ClojureScript, and others.
[src:koa/node-js] Node.js is primarily used to build network programs such as web servers.
[src:koa/node-js] The most significant difference between Node.js and PHP is that most functions in PHP block until completion (commands execute only after previous commands finish), while Node.js functions are non-blocking (commands execute concurrently and use callbacks to signal completion or failure).
[src:koa/node-js] Node.js is officially supported by Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows 8.1 and Server 2012 (and later), with Tier 2 support for SmartOS and IBM AIX and experimental support for FreeBSD.
[src:koa/node-js] OpenBSD also works, and LTS versions are available for IBM i (AS/400).
[src:koa/node-js] The source code may also be built on similar operating systems that are not officially supported, such as NonStop OS and Unix servers.
[src:koa/node-js] Node.js enables development of fast web servers in JavaScript using event-driven programming.
[src:koa/node-js] Developers can create scalable servers without using threading by using a simplified model that uses callbacks to signal the completion of a task.
[src:koa/node-js] Node.js connects the ease of a scripting language (JavaScript) with the power of Unix network programming.
[src:koa/node-js] Node.js was built on top of Google's V8 JavaScript engine since it was open-sourced under the BSD license, and it contains comprehensive support for fundamental protocols such as HTTP, DNS and TCP.
[src:koa/node-js] JavaScript's existing popularity made Node.js accessible to the web-development community.
[src:koa/node-js] There are thousands of open-source libraries for Node.js, most of which are hosted on the npm website.
[src:koa/node-js] Multiple developer conferences and events are held that support the Node.js community, including NodeConf, Node Interactive, and Node Summit, as well as a number of regional events.
[src:koa/node-js] The open-source community has developed web frameworks to accelerate the development of applications.
[src:koa/node-js] Such frameworks include Express.js, Socket.IO, Sails.js, Next.js and Meteor.
[src:koa/node-js] Various packages have also been created for interfacing with other languages or runtime environments such as Microsoft .NET.
[src:koa/node-js] Modern desktop IDEs provide editing and debugging features specifically for Node.js applications.
[src:koa/node-js] Such IDEs include Atom, Brackets, JetBrains WebStorm, Microsoft Visual Studio (with Node.js Tools for Visual Studio, or TypeScript with Node definitions), NetBeans, Nodeclipse Enide Studio (Eclipse-based) and Visual Studio Code.
[src:koa/node-js] Some online IDEs also support Node.js, such as Codeanywhere, Eclipse Che, Cloud9 IDE and the visual flow editor in Node-RED.
[src:koa/node-js] Node.js is supported across a number of cloud-hosting platforms such as Jelastic, Google Cloud Platform, AWS Elastic Beanstalk, Azure Web Apps and Joyent.
[src:koa/node-js] New major releases of Node.js are cut from the GitHub main branch every six months.
[src:koa/node-js] Even-numbered versions are cut in April and odd-numbered versions are cut in October.
[src:koa/node-js] When a new odd version is released, the previous even version undergoes transition to Long Term Support (LTS), which gives that version 12 months of active support from the date it is designated LTS.
[src:koa/node-js] After these 12 months expire, an LTS release receives an additional 18 months of maintenance support.
[src:koa/node-js] An active version receives non-breaking backports of changes a few weeks after they land in the current release.
[src:koa/node-js] A maintenance release receives only critical fixes and documentation updates.
[src:koa/node-js] The LTS Working Group manages strategy and policy in collaboration with the Technical Steering Committee of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:koa/node-js] Node.js is a JavaScript runtime environment that processes incoming requests in a loop, called the event loop.
[src:koa/node-js] Node.js uses libuv under the hood to handle asynchronous events.
[src:koa/node-js] Libuv is an abstraction layer for network and file system functionality on both Windows and POSIX-based systems such as Linux, macOS, OSS on NonStop, and Unix.
[src:koa/node-js] Node.js relies on nghttp2 for HTTP support.
[src:koa/node-js] As of version 20, Node.js uses the ada library which provides up-to-date WHATWG URL compliance.
[src:koa/node-js] As of version 19.5, Node.js uses the simdutf library for fast Unicode validation and transcoding.
[src:koa/node-js] As of version 21.3, Node.js uses the simdjson library for fast JSON parsing.
[src:koa/node-js] Node.js operates on a single-thread event loop, using non-blocking I/O calls, allowing it to support tens of thousands of concurrent connections without incurring the cost of thread context switching.
[src:koa/node-js] The design of sharing a single thread among all the requests that use the observer pattern is intended for building highly concurrent applications, where any function performing I/O must use a callback.
[src:koa/node-js] To accommodate the single-threaded event loop, Node.js uses the libuv library—which, in turn, uses a fixed-sized thread pool that handles some of the non-blocking asynchronous I/O operations.
[src:koa/node-js] A thread pool handles the execution of parallel tasks in Node.js.
[src:koa/node-js] The main thread function call posts tasks to the shared task queue, which threads in the thread pool pull and execute.
[src:koa/node-js] Inherently non-blocking system functions such as networking translate to kernel-side non-blocking sockets, while inherently blocking system functions such as file I/O run in a blocking way on their own threads.
[src:koa/node-js] When a thread in the thread pool completes a task, it informs the main thread of this, which in turn, wakes up and executes the registered callback.
[src:koa/node-js] A downside of this single-threaded approach is that Node.js does not allow vertical scaling by increasing the number of CPU cores of the machine it is running on without using an additional module, such as cluster, StrongLoop Process Manager, or pm2.
[src:koa/node-js] However, developers can increase the default number of threads in the libuv thread pool.
[src:koa/node-js] The server operating system (OS) is likely to distribute these threads across multiple cores.
[src:koa/node-js] Another problem is that long-lasting computations and other CPU-bound tasks freeze the entire event-loop until completion.
[src:koa/node-js] V8 is the JavaScript execution engine which was initially built for Google Chrome.
[src:koa/node-js] It was then open-sourced by Google in 2008.
[src:koa/node-js] Written in C++, V8 compiles JavaScript source code to native machine code at runtime.
[src:koa/node-js] As of 2016, it also includes Ignition, a bytecode interpreter.
[src:koa/node-js] npm is the pre-installed package manager for the Node.js server platform.
[src:koa/node-js] It installs Node.js programs from the npm registry, organizing the installation and management of third-party Node.js programs.
[src:koa/node-js] Node.js registers with the operating system so the OS notifies it of asynchronous I/O events such as new connections.
[src:koa/node-js] Within the Node.js runtime, events trigger callbacks and each connection is handled as a small heap allocation.
[src:koa/node-js] Traditionally, relatively heavyweight OS processes or threads handled each connection.
[src:koa/node-js] Node.js uses an event loop for concurrent I/O, instead of processes or threads.
[src:koa/node-js] In contrast to other event-driven servers, Node.js's event loop does not need to be called explicitly.
[src:koa/node-js] Instead, callbacks are defined, and the server automatically enters the event loop at the end of the callback definition.
[src:koa/node-js] Node.js exits the event loop when there are no further callbacks to be performed.
[src:koa/node-js] Node.js supports WebAssembly and as of Node 14 has experimental support of WASI, the WebAssembly System Interface.
[src:koa/node-js] Node.js provides a way to create "add-ons" via a C-based API called N-API, which can be used to produce loadable (importable) `.node` modules from source code written in C/C++.
[src:koa/node-js] The modules can be directly loaded into memory and executed from within JS environment as simple CommonJS modules.
[src:koa/node-js] The implementation of the N-API relies on internal C/C++ Node.js and V8 objects requiring users to import (#include) Node.js specific headers into their native source code.
[src:koa/node-js] As the Node.js API is subject to breaking changes at a binary level, modules have to be built and shipped against specific Node.js versions to work properly.
[src:koa/node-js] To address the issue, third parties have introduced open-sourced С/С++ wrappers on top of the API that partially alleviate the problem.
[src:koa/node-js] They simplify interfaces, but as a side effect they may also introduce complexity which maintainers have to deal with.
[src:koa/node-js] Even though the core functionality of Node.js resides in a JavaScript built-in library, modules written in C++ can be used to enhance capabilities and to improve performance of applications.
[src:koa/node-js] In order to produce such modules one needs to have an appropriate C++ compiler and necessary headers (the latter are typically shipped with Node.js itself), e.g., gcc, clang or MSVC++.
[src:koa/node-js] The N-API is similar to Java Native Interface.
[src:koa/node-js] OpenHarmony and ArkTS also adopts N-API, with the internal implementation rewritten.
[src:koa/node-js] In 2015, various branches of the greater Node.js community began working under the vendor-neutral Node.js Foundation.
[src:koa/node-js] The Node.js Foundation Technical Steering Committee (TSC) is the technical governing body of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:koa/node-js] The TSC is responsible for the core Node.js repo as well as dependent and adjacent projects.
[src:koa/node-js] Generally the TSC delegates the administration of these projects to working groups or committees.
[src:koa/node-js] The LTS group that manages long term supported releases is one such group.
[src:koa/node-js] Other current groups include Website, Streams, Build, Diagnostics, i18n, Evangelism, Docker, Addon API, Benchmarking, Post-mortem, Intl, Documentation, and Testing.
[src:koa/node-js] In August 2017, a third of the TSC members resigned due to a dispute related to the project's code of conduct.
[src:koa/node-js] They resigned after a vote failed to remove a member from the leadership group against whom multiple complaints had been filed.
